# Monetisation rules — locked

## The contract

- **Tenants are charged £0 platform fees, ever.**
- Tenants pay face-value rent only. Any fee from GoCardless / TrueLayer / Stripe is **absorbed by landlord or platform**.
- Landlords pay a single subscription via Stripe Billing.
- No rent take-rate. No tenant-side card surcharges. No premium tenant features.
- Rental Passport, rent dashboard, payments, messaging, tickets, and document access are **all free for tenants**.

## What this means in code

- No code path may charge a tenant for using a Tenantly feature.
- Rent payment flows quote face-value rent. The fee comes off the landlord's subscription invoice or the platform's books.
- "Premium" pricing tiers are **landlord-side only**. Tenant features never gate by tier.
- Subscription tier is an attribute of `org_subscriptions` (org-scoped), not user-scoped.

## Stripe

- One Stripe Customer per org.
- Tiers (Free, Starter, Pro, Portfolio) defined as Stripe Products + Prices.
- Webhooks update `org_subscriptions`.
- Tier capability matrix in `core/billing/capabilities.ts`. Used by both UI and server.

## GoCardless / TrueLayer

- Fee absorption logic in `core/billing/fee-absorption.ts`.
- Default: fee included in the landlord's monthly subscription invoice (added line item).
- For platform-absorbed cases (e.g., < 5 rooms), the platform pays.

## Tier enforcement

`tierGate(orgId, capability)` central helper. Server enforces; UI displays upsells (never blocking tenant features).

## Don't

- Don't add a "tenant pro" tier.
- Don't propose ads, marketplace fees on rent, or tenant-side data licensing.
- Don't charge tenants for Rental Passport export.
- Don't surcharge for late rent reminders.

This decision is locked in `docs/03-architecture/adr/0006-tenants-free-forever-monetisation.md`. It is the single most important product principle.

## When in doubt

If a feature seems to require charging a tenant, either:

1. The feature is in scope and we eat the cost ourselves (and document why).
2. The feature is in scope as a landlord-paid feature.
3. The feature is out of scope.

Never option 4: "tenant pays".
